{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "I will defend the idea that there is a properly epistemic form of alienation present in, and distinctive of, modern society.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Epistemic alienation is a subcategory of the kind of alienation outlined above, and one where the separation between subject and object involves some properly epistemic properties.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "The production of knowledge is increasingly a group activity and yet the forces that make groups good at producing knowledge are, to a non-trivial degree, in conflict with what it takes for individuals to be intellectually virtuous.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "As a result, maximal group efficiency often requires that a non-negligible number of group members behave in ways that are, at the level of individual virtue, non-virtuous.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The virtuous become alienated from fundamental epistemic goods.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "The paper therefore has two broad aims. First, to illustrate that the notion of epistemic alienation is fruitful ground for future research. Second, to highlight that the ‘social turn’ in epistemology is not without its costs: even if much—perhaps even most—of human knowledge is social in origin, its pursuit can nonetheless enable a form of alienation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Groups sometimes produce knowledge more efficiently when there is a non-negligible level of activity among members which, at the level of individuals, operates independently of the truth.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The forces of knowledge production place a relatively low cap on the amount of individually virtuous activity a group can accommodate before it starts to act as a drag on group success.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "The virtuous must either refrain from contributing to group knowledge (so as not to limit its efficiency) or contribute to group knowledge on bases other than their virtue.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "This separation between virtue and epistemic goods lies at the heart of my claim that the virtuous are epistemically alienated, since alienation involves a separation of a subject (in this case the virtuous) from an object (in this case fundamental epistemic goods).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The alienation of the virtuous therefore amounts to a distinctly modern form of alienation because the forces that give rise to it are distinctively modern.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "We have reached a time in human history where it is impossible to maintain all of our epistemic ideals simultaneously.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "The ideal of individual virtue and the ideal of knowledge production, though sometimes compatible, are not always so.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "A society prone to absurdities is a society that suffers from a social malady.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
